= Second Order Circuits
$
  C=0.01 mu F
  L=100 m H
$

== Fig 4-5
=== Fig 4-5 (a)
$
  s^2 + R/L s + 1/(L C) = 0\

  alpha = R/(2 L) = R/(2 times 100 m H) = 5R #h(5em) alpha^2 = 25R^2\
  omega_0^2 = 1/(L C) = 1/(100 m H times 0.01 mu F) = 1/10^(-9) = 1.0 times 10^9\
$

==== Over-damped response

$
  alpha^2 > omega_0^2\
  25R^2 > 1times 10^9\
  R^2 > 4 times 10^7\
  R < 6.32 k Omega
$
When $R < 6.32 k Omega$, the circuit is Over-damped

==== Critically-damped response

$
  alpha^2 = omega_0^2\
  R^2 = 4 times 10^7\
  R = 6.32 k Omega
$
When $R = 6.32 k Omega$, the circuit is Critically-damped

==== Under-damped response

$
  alpha^2 < omega_0^2\
  R^2 < 4 times 10^7\
  R > 6.32 k Omega
$
When $R > 6.32 k Omega$, the circuit is Under-damped

=== Fig 4-5 (b)
Characteristic equation:
$
  s^2 + 1/(R C) s + 1/(L C) = 0\

  alpha = 1/(2 R C) = 1/(2 times R times 0.01 mu F) = (5 times 10^7)/R\
  omega_0^2 = 1/(L C) = 1/(100 m H times 0.01 mu F) = 1/10^(-9) = 1.0 times 10^9\
$

==== Over-damped response

$
  alpha^2 > omega_0^2\
  (25 times 10^14)/R^2 > 1times 10^9\
  R < 1.58 k Omega
$
When $R < 1.58 k Omega$, the circuit is Over-damped

==== Critically-damped response

$
  alpha^2 = omega_0^2\
  R = 1.58 k Omega
$
When $R = 1.58 k Omega$, the circuit is Critically-damped

==== Under-damped response

$
  alpha^2 < omega_0^2\
  R^2 < 4 times 10^7\
  R > 1.58 k Omega
$
When $R > 1.58 k Omega$, the circuit is Under-damped

